export const chapterTranslations33to36: Record<number, string[]> = {
  "33": [
    "Shiji-shi took up his post, and Nanxiang went with him, planning to return the next year for the metropolitan exam. Famous scholars and celebrated actors saw them off, and after several more days of gatherings, time flew to mid–twelfth month. Ziyu, with Nanxiang and Gao Pin gone from the capital, had lost two close companions. The previous month, Academician Wang had told Lady Yan that Ziyu’s marriage would be completed either at winter’s end or in early spring.",
    "Lady Yan replied she could not decide alone and must write to Jiangxi first; only after receiving a reply could they settle the matter. Because of this, Ziyu also stopped visiting the Wang household as often. Xu Ziyun had recently filled an official vacancy and had more office duties, so he could no longer stay in the garden every day.",
    "One day, with clear weather, melting snow, and calm wind, Ziyu planned to visit Pincai and inquire about Qinyan.",
    "After breakfast he informed his mother and rode toward the city, but before going half a li he began to hesitate, thinking Pincai might not even be home. The more he thought, the gloomier he became, so he said, “Forget it—turn back out of the city.” Yun’er turned the horse, and as they came out they met a traffic jam of carriages and camels. Amid the shouting, Ziyu’s curtained carriage drew abreast of another. Looking through the glass window, he saw the other passenger turn as well—it was Baozhu. Smiling, Baozhu asked where he was coming from and where he was headed. Ziyu said he was returning from town and going nowhere now. Baozhu invited him to his lodging for a chat, saying they had not met in two months. Since it was still early, Ziyu agreed. With Ziyu’s carriage in front and Baozhu’s behind, they reached Baozhu’s place, got down, and Baozhu ushered him inside.",
    "It was Ziyu’s first visit. In the inner court he saw three main rooms; the western room was the study, with a plaque reading “Little Lang… Studio.” Inside, fragrance filled the air and there was not a speck of dust. Two pots of narcissus were in full bloom. On the table stood an antique bronze vase with nandina and wintersweet; nearby were more potted blooms. The calligraphy and paintings on the walls were all genuine works of earlier masters, nothing vulgar. In a niche hung Baozhu’s own portrait “Leaning on Bamboo,” and beside it four flower panels painted by Jin Su, his painting instructor. Ziyu sighed: “How strange fortune is. A man of such talent suffers such disaster—does Heaven truly envy talent this way?” He told Baozhu he had heard of Baozhu’s loyalty and support, especially after that gentleman’s misfortune, and praised his rare sincerity. Baozhu stayed silent, eyes reddening; he sighed, quoted, “We are both fallen people at the ends of the earth—why must prior acquaintance matter?” and began to cry. Realizing he had touched a sore point, Ziyu quickly changed the subject, pointing to bamboo outside and joking that only in winter could one see bamboo’s noble character beside decorative flowers. Baozhu laughed through tears. Ziyu then remarked how quickly the year had passed. Baozhu said he had heard from Jiantan that Ziyu would likely be congratulated after New Year and asked whether they would be invited to wedding wine. Ziyu said nothing was fixed until a family letter arrived. Baozhu then invited him to stay for dinner and said he would call Xiangwan (Sulan) to join them.",
    "Ziyu hesitated: if he stayed for dinner he would return too late. He suggested instead that, after the recent heavy snow, they should boil snow-water for tea and invite Sulan for a refined talk. Baozhu laughed and agreed, saying Ziyu was always different from others. He sent for Sulan and had a brazier, tea-stove, and full tea set brought out. A large bronze tray was laid down first, then an antique bronze stove was set on it, live coals kindled, and snow-water poured into a blue porcelain bowl and a carved Yixing kettle. Ziyu admired it and said the tea was not yet brewed, yet the sight already cleared one’s mind. Sulan arrived. He joked to Baozhu that such elegance must be for elegant guests, and adding a vulgar man like himself might spoil it. Baozhu said Sulan was elegant enough. Sulan asked Ziyu why he had stayed home lately and whether he had met Yunong (Qinyan). Ziyu said no; at present Yunong could hardly come out, and he had not expected Yunong to end up settled in that household. Baozhu replied that perhaps it was not truly Yunong’s settled place, since someone with Yunong’s aspirations could not bear long humiliation. Ziyu said he had heard Yunong was treated well. Baozhu said “well” was relative: Young Master Hua was not truly considerate, and if even Duxiang’s devotion could not fully satisfy Yunong, how could that side do as much?",
    "“The situation there is different in every way,” Baozhu said. “Everything is rule-bound, hard for someone used to freedom. On the fourteenth of the eighth month I saw Yunong come out to attend people—it was clearly forced.” Sulan added that now even when Yunong saw them, he still seemed depressed and closed-hearted. Ziyu sighed. When the water boiled, Baozhu personally mixed four famous teas in a jade tea vessel, brewed them, and poured three pale porcelain cups. Ziyu thanked him for the trouble. After tasting, both Ziyu and Sulan praised the fragrance and complexity. Baozhu explained he had blended several teas together. He then served fruit as accompaniment. They chatted, and Sulan asked whether Ziyu had seen his old family friend Wei Pincai recently. Ziyu said not for two months; he had in fact intended to visit him today but turned back. Baozhu teased that he should have gone—if Pincai were absent, “the one in your heart” would surely come out upon hearing Ziyu had arrived. Ziyu said nothing. Sulan then asked if he knew Pincai’s recent scandal. Ziyu asked what happened. Sulan said that although he had hated Pincai for sending men to harass Yunong, he had thought Pincai merely petty, not deeply evil—yet now Pincai had himself been disgraced and could hardly face people. Ziyu asked in shock what could be so shameful. Baozhu asked too. Sulan said friendship nowadays was dangerous because many people looked human but were beast-hearted: did they not know Wei Pincai had been seized in a prostitution case and sent to the Ministry of Punishments? Ziyu was stunned and asked why it had gone that far. Sulan said Zhang Zhongyu, now a command official, had told him about it four or five days ago.",
    "That night Pincai had invited Lord Fu Third to drink at Rongguan’s residence. Fu remembered other business and returned to the city first. Pincai stayed, had Rongguan summon a woman called Yu Tianxian, and planned to pass the night there. Near second watch they were still drinking and singing when clerk Yu Taisun came on night inspection. He knew Pincai and had dined and watched opera with him before. Pincai relaxed, invited him to sit, and joked with him when he refused. Yu suddenly turned stern: “Old Wei, no joking today. Do you understand official business must be done officially?” Pincai thought he was still joking and replied that even high officials drank with courtesans; why put on the inspector’s airs? He even tugged him to sit. Yu snorted: “Not just you—even if our chief censor were sitting here tonight, I’d arrest him.” At once constables chained Pincai and dragged him out; others shackled Rongguan and Yu Tianxian. Pincai, in a brand-new outfit, was tied behind a cart and made to run. At the clerk’s office he was interrogated harshly. Fortunately Pincai’s servants found a legal copyist, negotiated at 1,600 strings, wrote bonds, and found guarantors before the shackles were removed. They fabricated testimony: “Wei Pincai” became “Li Sancai,” and the gathering was recast as an ordinary meal where Rongguan’s married sister happened to visit, causing mixed company but no illicit banquet.",
    "Ziyu said, “If the facts were clarified that way, why was it still sent up?” Sulan answered that a city patrol superior discovered the clerk had extorted money, altered testimony, and privately released suspects, so the case was reopened and sent to the Ministry. Baozhu asked whether Pincai was now jailed; “Serves him right—but why didn’t Young Master Hua intervene?”",
    "Sulan said Zhongyu reported the matter had been concealed from Young Master Hua, and the false name made it harder to trace at first. Pincai would lose face regardless; perhaps the criminal penalty would not be severe, but he had recently purchased a rank and might lose that title if convicted. Ziyu, worried for him, said this was terrible; even their acquaintance Li had recently made a fool of himself in similar debauchery, and now Pincai too had caused scandal. Sulan replied it was deserved retribution—he once used coachmen to torment others, and now it returned doubled. Ziyu laughed in spite of himself.",
    "After chatting for a long while, Ziyu saw it was getting late, took leave of the two, and returned home.",
    "At home, Lady Yan looked displeased. Ziyu dared not ask and stood silently. She said a family letter from his father had arrived and his father now knew all of Ziyu’s conduct, blaming her for failing to discipline him; she handed Ziyu the letter. Before reading it he was already terrified. After reading, his face flushed bright red; he stood speechless, only looking at his mother. Pitying him but forcing sternness, she said if he knew fear he should not have done such things in the first place; whether he corrected himself was up to him, but when his father returned he might not be so lenient. Ziyu could only answer “Yes, yes” repeatedly, neither daring to sit nor withdraw. Unable to comfort him directly, Lady Yan asked whether he had seen Wei Pincai today.",
    "Ziyu hesitated; when pressed, he said he had not seen Pincai and had heard Pincai had been accused and jailed at the Ministry. Lady Yan was alarmed and demanded who said this and for what reason. Ziyu said Zhang Zhongyu, a relative of Pincai, had said so—apparently a case involving drinking with prostitutes and arrest by ward officers. Lady Yan cursed him as shameless and wondered whether the Hua household did nothing. Ziyu said Pincai often stayed outside the city, had used a false surname Li, and likely kept the matter hidden from Hua; people also said he had recently purchased a minor rank. Though he called himself Li Sancai, everyone knew he was Wei Pincai. Lady Yan flushed with anger and complained all these young men were worthless; even Li was rarely home and likely up to no good. Still, though Pincai was not worth much, he was the son of her husband’s old associate, so they should verify facts and try to help. She summoned servant Mei Jin and told him to visit Elder Wang by marriage and ask for intervention at the Ministry. Mei Jin said he would go, but noted the detention was unusually strict—family could not even deliver food—so Wang might refuse to intercede; perhaps the Hua side would handle it. Asked what he knew, Mei Jin recounted the whole story in detail. Lady Yan said regardless, they must do their part, and sent him anyway. After he left, she coldly remarked this was the model outcome of frequenting actor households. Ziyu blushed with shame, sat quietly, attended his mother through dinner, and returned to his study. Frightened at heart, he dared not indulge wild thoughts for several days.",
    "Mei Jin went to the Wang residence. Wenhui received him, heard the request, and sneered: he had known at first sight Wei Pincai was no good; they had insisted on keeping him, and now at least he was gone. With no personal channels at the Ministry, he could only ask others and let fate decide. Mei Jin reported this honestly on return; Lady Yan had no choice but to let events run their course. Meanwhile, in jail, Pincai promised Rongguan and Yu Tianxian large sums to follow his testimony: that clerk Yu had invited them to drink and then demanded a loan of one thousand taels from Pincai; when refused, a quarrel followed.",
    "Their statement continued: Yu had brought constables in advance, shackled them, and took them away, then recast it as a lawful night arrest while extorting money and forcing debt notes. Yu Tianxian further testified that Yu often visited her home to smoke and drink; half a month earlier he had sent invitations for a cash contribution, but when money did not arrive he held a grudge and arranged this arrest in retaliation.",
    "They said that after the arrest Yu demanded another five hundred strings to alter testimony and release them. Rongguan testified the same. The Ministry held two hearings and cross-checked statements. Young Master Hua had by then learned of the affair; though inclined to ignore it, he felt uneasy and sent people to intercede, resulting in lighter penalties. Clerk Yu was dismissed; Pincai received twenty strokes; Yu Tianxian was expelled beyond jurisdiction; Rongguan was released home. The case was closed.",
    "Pincai returned to town in high spirits, boasting that he had “won the lawsuit,” and went straight back to the Hua residence.",
    "Gate attendants offered consoling words. Pincai swaggered that he had suffered no real grievance because all the officials were his friends, even the jail warden his close associate, and everything had been smoothed over through connections. He asked whether the young master knew of it; the attendants could only answer they did not know.",
    "Back in his room, people came in groups to inquire after him, but no message came from Young Master Hua. Pincai took this as proof the master knew nothing and relaxed. On the third day Lin Shanzhi entered carrying a large wrapped package, set it down, and said only, “This is from the young master,” then left before Pincai could even thank him. The unusual manner disturbed him. He checked the wrapping: “Traveling gift, two hundred taels.” His heart jolted. After reflection he understood the meaning, but did not know how to respond and waited for a chance to clarify.",
    "After waiting two days with no visitor—not even usual acquaintances Gu Yueqing and Zhang Xiaomei—he spent half the night deciding what to do. Next morning he wrote a thanks note: first gratitude, then an excuse that family matters at the Mei house required his temporary return; he would come back in spring. He delivered it through the gate office. About half an hour later the gatekeeper returned: the young master had read it and agreed returning to Mei house was appropriate; he was too busy to see him off personally. Pincai had still hoped for reconciliation; hearing this, he felt ashes in his heart. He thanked everyone for half a year’s care and said he would move out that day without formal farewell. With no choice, he packed, hired a large cart, and left the city with one horse, two pages, a cook, and a driver, lodging temporarily at an inn before finding new quarters.",
    "Pincai had stayed at the Hua house only ten months, yet through bluff and petty swindling he had amassed considerable money. Beyond regular stipend, Young Master Hua had given many gifts. Pincai spent over four hundred taels buying a minor rank, and roughly two thousand more on clothes and extravagance. Even so, after receiving that two-hundred-tael farewell gift he still had about three hundred taels and various valuables. Since his purchased rank stood high on the list and might be assigned within half a year, his confidence swelled. After two noisy days at the inn, he rented Chunhang’s old rooms at Hongji Temple, put on grand style with carriage and horse, and did not even visit the Mei house. Rongguan and Yu Tianxian came and went often; he gave each money and trinkets, feasting and drinking daily, naturally drawing a circle of similarly dissolute companions.",
    "When Lord Fu Third heard of Pincai’s trouble, he had inquired at the Ministry but found no channel; only after hearing Young Master Hua had interceded did he relax. Later hearing Pincai had left Hua’s residence, he worried again and wanted to bring him home. One morning he went out to the temple and found commotion at the gate: a man in shabby sheepskin coat and old cap was cursing loudly, complaining he had served diligently yet was promised one hundred strings and paid only thirty, threatening revenge if called again. Fu recognized him as a prison guard and entered frowning. Pincai’s people announced him. Inside he heard clappers and noisy merriment. Rongguan came out with Pincai; Rongguan flirtatiously reached for Fu’s hand, and they joked roughly. Fu then congratulated Pincai and said he had worried much, and asked his plans: seek another post, stay outside the city, or come live with him through New Year? Pincai thanked him but said staying outside was more convenient for now. Fu asked if he had enough travel funds and advised economy since he had grown used to Hua-house luxury. Pincai agreed and offered to dine in-house. Fu suggested a restaurant, but Rongguan laughed that it was already the twenty-fifth of the twelfth month—restaurants had closed for year-end collections. Fu admitted his troubled mind had made him forget dates. Asked what troubled him, Fu said not New Year itself but his pending assignment: two vacancies had opened, Hubei and Guizhou. Hubei was desirable, Guizhou harsh. By order he should get Hubei, but a senior candidate had inserted himself. Guizhou’s revenues were said to be miserable. Could he lobby the Selection Office? Pincai said the temple monk had a brother who was a clerk in the Personnel Ministry selection bureau; perhaps they could ask him to reverse it. Fu agreed and asked Pincai to speak to the monk on his behalf, promising heavy thanks if successful. Pincai said the monk was easy to talk with—hardly monk-like, adept in drink, women, gambling, singing, and even venereal treatment, lively and useful.",
    "People called him Master Tang, though he preferred “Brother Tang.” As Pincai spoke, the wind-door creaked and a head in a brown felt cap with thick mustache peered in, then withdrew. Pincai called him in. He first declined, then entered when told Lord Fu was present and wished to meet him. Smiling broadly, the monk greeted Fu as a great man; Fu returned the courtesy. Tang sat and looked Fu over. Fu in turn noted Tang’s odd appearance: short and stocky, blue monk robe, yellow sash, gray fur-lined shoes, crafty lines on his face, lustful eyes, and a white-jade snuff bottle. They exchanged snuff. Tang claimed old ties: his late master had been close to Fu’s father, who used to visit the temple and play go; a calligraphic couplet by Fu’s father still hung there. He asked where Fu currently served. Fu said he had worked in Revenue and now had purchased a prefectural appointment awaiting assignment. Tang asked province; Fu said undecided between Hubei and Guizhou. Tang immediately declared Fu would surely get Hubei—his own native place—and laughed. Pincai said Tang should stay for the meal and discuss a matter. They spoke privately; Fu could hear enough to know Tang was promising full assistance. Tang then told Fu he would call his younger brother to handle things and guaranteed success without Fu’s worry. Just then a young novice of sixteen or seventeen entered, strikingly pretty, in fine warm monk attire with bright red-edged shoes, carrying a water pipe to pack tobacco for his master. Tang began smoking without yielding to guests. Fu stared at the youth with obvious desire. Rongguan, behind Pincai, made gestures teasing Fu, who smiled and asked Tang if this was his disciple, saying he seemed familiar.",
    "Tang proudly said the novice was called Deyue, fifteen years old, passable at chanting and singing, but mischievous, so he was usually not allowed out. Fu, squinting with a smile, pretended to think and suddenly laughed, saying he had mistaken the boy for a nun from Great Compassion Convent because he looked so similar. Pincai roared with laughter; the novice blushed crimson. Tang laughed it off. Pincai joked that if dressed as a nun no one could tell. He praised Tang as a man of perfect pleasures in food, dress, use, and play. Tang replied with mock piety that monks were no saints now. His elder monk-brother had once restricted him, but after his death life became freer. The elder had hoarded rent and lived austerely only to be cheated by his nephew and die empty-handed, while Tang handled funeral matters. Better, Tang said, to enjoy life while alive; modern monks were meat-and-wine monks anyway, and he himself did not hide that he tasted drink, women, and gambling. Fu laughed and called him refreshingly frank. As they talked, Fu kept eyeing the lovely novice with growing lust, especially seeing him whispering closely with Rongguan on the same bench.",
    "By noon, Pincai’s servants finally laid the table. Fu said not to make too much fuss; Pincai answered there was little to eat anyway. They took seats as host and guests; Fu had Deyue seated too. Tang told Deyue and Rongguan to pour wine. Seeing the table piled with snacks, Fu told them to remove most and keep only four dishes. Rongguan protested and snatched a dish of oranges and kumquats, saying others liked them. Nine hot dishes followed and were quite tasty. Rongguan fed Tang a meatball, then another; Tang swallowed both whole. Rongguan made a lewd joke, prompting laughter from Fu and Pincai. Tang returned with even grosser teasing and grabbed Rongguan. Rongguan pulled off Tang’s cap, rubbed his bald head, and asked what it looked like; Tang answered with obscene banter. Rongguan called him a “thieving bald monk.” After a few cups Deyue’s face reddened and he looked even more charming. Fu praised Deyue’s refined look; Rongguan teased whether Fu wanted to “take him as apprentice” (innuendo). They carried on boisterously. Eventually Tang’s opium craving hit, so he lit a pipe at Pincai’s place and smoked; the party dispersed only near late afternoon.",
    "Fu returned to the city after again entrusting matters to Monk Tang; Rongguan also left. What happened afterward is told in the next chapter."
  ],
  "34": [
    "After seeing Fu Third off, Pincai had Monk Tang summon Tang’s younger brother. Pincai had just stepped back inside when Li Yuanmao burst in, saying he had finally found him after searching many places, only to learn he had moved here. Pincai said he had moved only recently and had been busy, so he had not yet visited Yuanmao or Yuxiang. He asked how Yuxiang was. Yuanmao said he was fine, and that last month the Wang family had written to the elders, planning to complete Yuxiang’s marriage in the second or third month of next year. As for Yuanmao’s own marriage, the Sun family kept pressing; both sides were no longer young, yet his petition home still had no reply.",
    "For half a year no money had come from home, Yuanmao said; now it was already the twenty-fifth, and even if a letter came this year it might arrive too late. He owed over forty strings to restaurants and another twenty to thirty in miscellaneous costs; he had pawned clothes and needed to redeem at least two decent pieces for New Year calls. He begged Pincai to help him. Pincai said he himself had just spent heavily dealing with extortion trouble, was idle now, and had no cash at all. Yuanmao accused him of pretending poverty and begged for forty taels or a hundred strings, promising repayment once family money came (at least five hundred taels for marriage). Pincai laughed coldly, saying Yuanmao treated him as rich without reason; he had debts in the hundreds of strings. He pulled out account slips from his boot. Yuanmao saw over two hundred strings owed to tailors, another two hundred to eateries and lodgings, plus many smaller debts, totaling over five hundred strings. Pincai said this was not even complete—counting lodging expenses and New Year costs, he needed around eight hundred strings. With empty hands and only a few fur garments he still needed to wear, he could not save others. He asked whether Yuanmao might instead borrow through his two brothers-in-law. Yuanmao sighed that those “treasures” only ate and drank for free; even Elder Sun owed debts and was hiding. After rambling on, Yuanmao stayed for dinner. Then he found opium gear in Pincai’s room and started smoking, making noisy demands for fruit and snacks and calling the servant Si’er endlessly, irritating Pincai. By second watch Pincai urged him to go home before gates closed. Yuanmao refused and insisted on sleeping there, proposing they share bedding and talk as in old days. Pincai had no choice. Yuanmao remained shamelessly demanding while Pincai lay aside and ignored him.",
    "At third watch, Si’er came saying Monk Tang invited Pincai for a talk. In Tang’s room, candles and a stove burned brightly; leftovers and a liquor pot sat on a side table, but Tang was absent at first. He arrived shortly, apologizing for sudden stomach trouble, washed, then sat down. He said he had spoken to his brother about Fu Third’s assignment: both vacancies arrived same day, with Hubei ranked first. They could manipulate order to place Guizhou first instead. That was still corruption, so his brother would not do it for free for a man with no personal tie. Since Guizhou was worth far less than one year in Hubei, everyone knew the value. Tang told Pincai to relay this. Pincai asked if it was reliable. Tang said absolutely; payment would be due only upon success. Asked price, Tang said strangers might pay three to five thousand taels, but as Tang’s friend Fu would be charged only three thousand strings (about twelve hundred taels). Given that the post could yield twenty thousand taels in informal gains upon arrival, this fee was small. Fu should issue draft notes for that amount; once done, Tang sought no extra, just hospitality for a few days.",
    "Pincai calculated and asked whether the sum could be reduced if Fu balked. Tang said it was already reduced to the limit and only his brother could decide; Pincai should tell Fu first thing in the morning. The matter moved fast—audience could be on the twenty-ninth. They must operate skillfully and avoid later reversals: Fu should place funds in a money shop immediately with delayed pickup terms. Once success occurred, disputes over amounts would look ugly. Pincai agreed. Returning to his room, he found Yuanmao sleeping loudly in his clothes. He woke him, gave him separate bedding, and lay down himself. Thinking over Fu’s affair and his own debts, he did not truly settle until near fifth watch. After a brief sleep he rose at dawn, ordered carriage harnessed, washed, ate, dressed, while Yuanmao still slept.",
    "Pincai shook Yuanmao awake and said he was going into town and no one would attend him. Yuanmao muttered, turned over, covered his head, and went back to sleep. Irritated, Pincai saw he would not rise, so he left Si’er to watch the house and went out with a page on horseback to find Fu Third.",
    "Yuanmao slept until late morning. Seeing Si’er cleaning, he asked where his master had gone. Si’er said to Fu Third’s place. Yuanmao dressed and moved to the outer room; Si’er brought wash water, tea, and snacks. Yuanmao smoked several bowls, spat all over, and Si’er cleaned again. Asked when Pincai would return, Si’er said uncertain. Yuanmao said he had important things left unsaid last night and would wait there rather than miss him again. He asked for food. Si’er said household staff had eaten but he would tell the cook. Shortly after, Si’er brought a tray of dishes and asked whether to serve liquor. Yuanmao asked for just two liang of spirits.",
    "Si’er set the dishes—smoked chicken, eggs, shredded meat, and gluten—then brought a small flask and cup, poured, and left. Drinking, Yuanmao began studying the furnishings, which were quite refined. Last night he had not noticed due to distraction. The outer suite had small rooms; Pincai’s sleeping quarters were in two rooms through another gate on the west side. Sitting on the heated kang, after three or four cups he grew tipsy and looked around carefully: miniature New-Year paintings above the kang, a striking clock on the kang table, nanmu chairs and tea tables with narcissus and wintersweet, couplets on the wall, polished copper spittoons by a window table, glass-inlaid curtain panel and windows, blue satin cushions, and musical instruments hanging on walls. Curious, he entered the inner room through gauze windows and a blue silk curtain. It was larger: a bed under an ice-pattern frame, pale drapes, piled brocade quilts, clothing bundles, a rosewood kang table with red brocade cushions, and a “sleeping beauty” painting. On the west side sat four large leather trunks topped with two small wooden cases, plus two cabinets below; a large bronze brazier stood center. By the window was a desk with two sets of small books; the slip labels read *Jin Ping Mei*.",
    "There was also a writing tray with brush and inkstone. A large glass pane sat in the central window; a small shelf held odds and ends; two square stools below wore blue satin covers. After seeing all this, Yuanmao thought: “How can he claim poverty? Those trunks must hold lots of clothes, and the wooden boxes and cabinets must store silver and cash. He’s pretending poor to fool me—I won’t let him off today.” He returned outside. Si’er brought more dishes and rice: mutton and stir-fried liver; later the cook added a small hotpot. Yuanmao ate five bowls of rice, much soup, most of a bowl of mutton, rinsed his mouth, smoked again, chewed betel for a long while, and still did not leave.",
    "Meanwhile Pincai reached Fu Third’s house and said success was assured. Fu was delighted. Asked cost, Pincai said the other side claimed the post yielded thirty thousand by custom, so one-tenth was reasonable; they demanded three thousand taels, and despite his pleading had only reduced to eighty percent—2,400 taels. Fu considered this acceptable and asked timing. Pincai said the money was due upon twenty-ninth presentation, but drafts were needed today, dated for pickup on the thirtieth. Fu asked who would hold drafts. Pincai said he and the monk would hold them as guarantors. Fu asked what if it failed. Pincai guaranteed return of original drafts and said Fu could cancel at the shop on the twenty-ninth first. Fu agreed but noted year-end liquidity was tight; they should eat and go immediately to the silver houses. After eating, Pincai urged haste. Fu rode in Pincai’s carriage to a nearby exchange house. Over tea, Fu requested a draft for 2,400 taels payable on the morning of the thirtieth.",
    "The manager said this would have been easy two days earlier, but now, on the twenty-sixth, funds were tight and difficult to gather. Fu protested that if this large house couldn’t do it, who could? The manager replied all exchange houses were short of silver; outside receivables had not come back. They could provide whatever amount they could collect. Fu asked what amount to write. The manager suggested skipping drafts and settling directly on the thirtieth. Fu refused: he needed drafts for debt repayment. If full 2,400 was impossible, issue 2,000, or even 1,500–1,600, and he would cover the rest elsewhere; if unused, he would cancel on the twenty-ninth.",
    "The manager agreed and issued drafts totaling 1,400 taels. Pincai advised splitting them into two 500s and one 400 in case recipients could not cash large amounts before year-end. Fu agreed. They then visited two more exchange houses, both refusing. With no options and no relationship at other houses, Fu went home, consulted Third Madam, and gathered valuables—forty taels of gold leaves, a pair of gold bracelets, and other pieces totaling sixty taels—converted at a pawn/metal shop into 1,000 taels silver and obtained additional drafts. Pincai again advised splitting: 500, 300, and 200. Fu handed all drafts to Pincai. Pincai, intent on business, left at once and rode back out of the city.",
    "Back at his lodging, Pincai first met Monk Tang, reported terms, then produced three drafts totaling 1,200 taels for Tang to keep, with the agreement to return them if failure occurred on the twenty-ninth. Tang grinned and said success was certain; they themselves deserved the extra 200 and needed to pass only 1,000 onward. Pincai went to change clothes and found Yuanmao still there smoking with lamps lit in daytime. Angry, he scolded him for displaying such things openly in a temple where anyone could walk in and possibly extort them both. Yuanmao said there was nothing to fear and no one had come all day, with Si’er watching outside. Pincai, too annoyed to argue, changed furs and cap, washed, drank tea. Yuanmao resumed begging for money; when repeatedly refused, he hinted at Pincai’s trunks and asked for only around a hundred strings. Badgered beyond endurance, Pincai took a twisted gold bracelet from a small box—about 3.6 taels—and told Yuanmao to pawn it for over a hundred strings, but repay once family letters and money arrived. Yuanmao accepted happily and finally left.",
    "On the twenty-ninth, Fu indeed got Hubei. All were delighted; he came to the temple to thank Pincai and Tang. Next day he delivered drafts to Tang’s brother, who further deducted 200 from the 1,000 as “handling costs” and pocketed it. Of the remaining 200 surplus, he gave 100 to Pincai. In effect Pincai netted 1,300 taels. He went into town, converted half to cash, changed some into copper outside town, and strutted in triumph. He paid all debts and celebrated New Year lavishly. That evening he even brought Yu Tianxian into the temple and invited Monk Tang to keep New Year with him, shutting the temple gate early. Firecrackers and tube-flares sounded all night.",
    "Tang worried that on New Year’s morning worshippers might come and see Yu Tianxian inside the temple, which would be awkward. Near dawn he urged Pincai to send her back by carriage immediately.",
    "Pincai paid New Year visits on the first day, watched opera on the second, and on the third hosted grand banquets, inviting drifters like Feng Zipei, Yang Meichuang, Wu Dasha and others with a crowd of low performers. They drank and caroused daily with music and noise like a riot of strings and percussion, five days straight, burning about three hundred strings. On the ninth, someone proposed opening gambling and urged Pincai to bankroll it. Thinking his luck was strong, Pincai agreed. That night they ran games—wheel betting, dice, and more—and brought Yu Tianxian to sit inside and run side-stakes with him. Attendance was small day one, larger day two, and packed by day three. Word spread from one to two to three, drawing two major gamblers: Xi Eleven and Pan Third, both bringing heavy funds.",
    "That day Pincai won over two hundred taels and took in 180 taels in banker’s rake with Yu Tianxian.",
    "Next day Pan Third hosted, bringing two trays of Songjiang ingots—full thousand taels. After fifty rounds he had lost most; by settlement he had lost all and owed another hundred-plus taels. That day Pincai himself lost three hundred taels. Monk Tang won one hundred, Feng Zipei four hundred.",
    "Xi Eleven won big—over 850 taels. He tipped over fifty taels among young actors and Pincai’s pages, pocketing 800. Fancying the novice monk, he tipped him ten medium ingots. Yu Tianxian also took 240 taels in side-commission. Among those present was Tang Jingsheng, the monk’s brother, who warned Tang that two suspicious men outside looked like ward officers; better stop gambling tomorrow before trouble came. Pincai, already skittish from past arrests, became afraid and said they should pause a couple days. Tang said if they were merely tired, fine, but no need to fear external trouble. He explained there was a large vegetable garden beside Pincai’s quarters with huts and another exit; the inner gate had been locked only for caution. If anything happened, they could open it and slip out through open fields—hardly as if troops would besiege them. Pincai said his pause was not from losses or fear but because Fu Third was departing and he wanted a farewell banquet on the fourteenth, inviting Fu to stay overnight. He invited Xi and Pan to join; both agreed. Feng Zipei complained at not being formally invited; Pincai said he was there daily anyway. Zipei said he would bring Meichuang. Pincai agreed. After settling accounts, gamblers dispersed around fifth watch, and Yu Tianxian was sent back.",
    "Feng Zipei slept in the same bed with Pincai. Pincai said that lately too many people chased reputation and ignored practical reality. Men like Young Master Hua and Xu Duxiang spent money like dirt in grand-official style, yet treated actors too respectfully, almost as social equals.",
    "He continued: bookish fools like Tian Chunhang kept elevating actors until one could not joke with them at all. Actors then put on fake refinement, speaking of soulmates and intimates, pretending to calligraphy, painting, qin, and chess, no longer even greeting patrons properly. Pincai said he did not believe they behaved that way with rough men—they only fooled nerdy patrons, who in turn corrupted the whole hierarchy. Zipei agreed: if this continued, who would hire them? Could actors live forever only on men like Xu Duxiang? Never knowing powerful, profitable patrons made them true fools. Pincai said he would host another grand gathering and wanted no fake refined types; whom should they call?",
    "Zipei replied that actors were mostly alike, but two newcomers were good, cheap to hire, and could be summoned often; their looks rivaled Yuan Baozhu and Su Huifang. Their names were Zhuo Tianxiang and Zhang Cuiguan, from the “Zhengrong troupe.” Pincai said he had never heard of it. Zipei explained they were young barber apprentices from soft-canopy stalls. Pincai scoffed. Zipei said not to underestimate them—they were hotter than regular actors. Pincai admitted Deyue looked good but disliked shaved heads. Zipei said Tianxiang and Cuiguan looked even better; he would bring them next day for Pincai to judge. Pincai agreed.",
    "Next day Pincai sent invitations to Fu Third, Gui Da-ye, Xi Eleven, Pan Third, Zhang Zhongyu, and Yang Meichuang. Two declined (Gui ill, Zhang occupied), so Feng Zipei and Monk Tang filled in, making seven total. Pincai had Rongguan attend Fu and sent for Tianxiang and Cuiguan. Soon the two barber-youths arrived by mule cart with an attendant. Knowing Zipei, they greeted him first, then Pincai. Pincai inspected them carefully: both handsome and fashionably dressed like actors, with jewelry and watches. Tianxiang had fair but slightly coarse skin; Cuiguan was quick and charming, with freckles and a mole, and rougher hands. Pincai liked them more as he watched. Zipei told them to come next day to pour wine. They fawned eagerly—packing pipes, pouring tea, even massaging backs and legs. Pincai was delighted and kept them for supper. Both could sing local opera and play fiddle and moon-lute; music and noise ran until third watch. Pincai paid each eight strings and dismissed them.",
    "Early next morning they came to serve before Pincai and Zipei had risen. The two barbers asked for combs, dressed Pincai’s hair, then massaged him; one did the same for Zipei. After breakfast they lit opium lamps. Fu Third arrived first; Monk Tang then entered with Deyue. Tianxiang and Cuiguan greeted Fu and Tang. Fu did not recognize them and asked what troupe they belonged to; Pincai said “Quanfu troupe.” Soon Xi Eleven and Pan Third arrived; Xi brought Ba Yingguan, Pan brought a young apprentice as attendant. Pan joked at seeing Tianxiang and Cuiguan there. Xi quipped that Wei Da-ye seemed ready to open his own “canopy house” as manager. Fu then realized they were barbers, not opera actors, and laughed that this was fine too. They all sat joking for a while.",
    "Someone shouted in the courtyard, “Late! I’m late!” A man in fur robe and huge fur cap entered bowing—it was Yang Eight, saying an inner-city friend had dragged him around all day to inspect houses and land, likely seeking a favorable posting. Pincai introduced him to Tianxiang and Cuiguan as a fengshui expert and joked they should ask him when their stall would prosper. Fu joked Yang should be careful not to end up like “the Wu family case.” Everyone laughed. Suddenly Feng Zipei frowned, said he felt bad, and rushed outside to vomit. The group hurried to him; after retching he was flushed, dizzy, feverish. Pincai had him lie on the kang, but he worsened and requested to leave, so a carriage was arranged to send him home. Near lamp-lighting time, Pincai ordered all lights lit. He had newly made a glass lamp-screen painted with twenty-four erotic scenes; eight glass lamps hung in the room with a colored central lamp, four floor-lights below, braziers at both sides, and a round banquet table in center. As they sat, Xi Eleven pointed to one painting and joked to Pan Third that the slapped face looked like him; Pan retorted another embracing figure looked like Xi, just lacking a “bucket” prop. Fu saw the final panel and burst out laughing: “Outrageous! Wei old-brother shouldn’t have hung this so fittingly—come look, isn’t this two monks buggering each other?”",
    "Everyone laughed. Xi Eleven teased Deyue, asking whether his master did this every day. Deyue spat “pah,” blushed, and turned away. Monk Tang folded his palms and muttered, “Amitabha—sin, sin.” Seating was arranged: Fu Third first seat with Cuiguan attending; Xi second with Deyue (Tang knew Xi was rich and liked Deyue); Yang Eight third with Tianxiang beside him; Pan fourth; Pincai and Tang at host positions. Rongguan was absent. Drinking quickly turned into vulgar shouting and abuse. Fu was relatively restrained, joking with Cuiguan without descending fully into coarseness. Xi forced Deyue to drink while groping him from behind; Deyue twisted and resisted, eyes watery, hand pushing the cup. Xi threatened to force a “skin-cup” if he refused, so Deyue drank. Yang Eight was worse, pulling Tianxiang onto his lap, bouncing his leg so Tianxiang shook all over, drinking mouth-to-mouth and prying into rumors about Tianxiang’s sister’s beauty and connections. Tianxiang blushed and denied rumors; Yang mocked that if people had even written fans for her, could all that also be false?",
    "As he spoke, Yang leaned in to sniff Tianxiang’s face again. Only Pan Third and Pincai lacked direct playmates. Pincai laughed that they should take turns teasing the old monk, and they played finger-forfeit games with Tang. After over an hour, Xi Eleven’s opium craving rose; he had Ba Yingguan bring the gear. Since lamps were already lit, Xi lay down and had Deyue accompany him while smoking. The two barbers, also addicted, crowded in too. Seeing this, Tang yawned twice and stretched; unable to wait for his own craving, he went to his room to smoke first.",
    "Fu Third leaned over and asked Cuiguan whether this trade offered any real future, and whether he would go with Fu to Hubei instead. Cuiguan said if Fu truly took him, he would treat him like a real father, then nestled into Fu’s arms and asked again earnestly. Unlike formal actors requiring costly release fees, he said, his apprenticeship term was only three years and now complete, so he could leave freely. Fu promised to take him if willing. Yang Eight interrupted, saying Fu was fooling around and should spend that money helping Yang purchase a distributive appointment instead; he asked Fu to add another contribution line to a previous subscription list. Fu said he would add thirty taels and told Yang not to be jealous. Yang, rather than offended, thanked him repeatedly.",
    "Cuiguan laughed: “Third Master, what fortune you have—I call you one godfather and immediately recruit you another dependent.” Yang pretended not to hear and sat aside smoking water tobacco.",
    "Pincai encouraged Cuiguan, saying following Fu was good and he should have no hesitation; though not formal actor release, they should still tip his master a few strings. Fu agreed. Cuiguan asked if it was truly settled. Fu said yes. Cuiguan climbed onto him, rubbing his head against Fu’s shoulder and thanking him as “dear father,” which delighted Fu immensely. Pan Third, seeing Deyue in Xi’s arms and Tianxiang opposite, moved to the kang edge and leaned onto Tianxiang while Yang Eight wanted a puff too. After Deyue prepared the pipe, Yang took it, parted his thick beard, drew once, drooled all over pipe and mouthpiece, wiped himself with his fur sleeve, then drew again. The pipe clogged; Tianxiang tried to clear it but Yang’s weight pinned him. Yang grabbed a pick and jabbed wildly, accidentally singeing his own fur sleeve on the lamp, making everyone laugh.",
    "Yang Eight said he was a beginner, took another rough puff, burned it badly, and set the pipe down. Tianxiang told him to stop pressing on him so he could tend the bowl properly. Over there Deyue lay with his head on Xi Eleven’s arm while Xi kept groping him; when Deyue tried to rise, Xi pinned him with a leg, forcing him to endure it. Xi finished one full box of opium and called for more. Ba Yingguan stood at a distance sulking. Xi called several times before he answered there was none left. Xi said impossible—there was a larger box in the bag. After another pause Yingguan said it had spilled. Xi demanded to see the box.",
    "Angrily, Ba Yingguan came over and flung the big gold box; it flipped and rolled near the lamp.",
    "When Deyue rushed to retrieve it, he accidentally knocked over the lamp with a crash, shattering the glass chimney and splashing oil onto Xi Eleven’s face. Embarrassed, Deyue apologized; Xi said it was fine, wiped quickly, asked for water, and cleaned his face. Oil spots on his lynx-fur coat were also wiped off. Pincai’s servants replaced the lamp and cleaned the tray. Opening the box, Deyue found it truly empty. Xi asked what now and suggested borrowing from Master Tang. Pincai said he had some old native opium and sent Si’er to fetch it.",
    "Pincai’s own rooms were west of this courtyard, through another gate into a small yard with two rooms. He had only locked the yard gate; busy serving guests, he had not stationed a guard inside.",
    "The moon that night was bright as day. Si’er went to the gate, unlocked it, and pushed—but the door would not open. Usually it moved easily; tonight it was stuck fast, and even with extra force it barely moved.",
    "Setting down the lamp cover, Si’er shoved hard with both hands and forced the door partly open, discovering a stone braced behind it. He was baffled—if no one was inside, who had set the stone? He crouched, removed it, picked up the lamp cover, and checked the outer room: at first glance things seemed intact and he relaxed slightly. But when he examined the inner room carefully, he was terrified: one large leather trunk was gone, along with two caskets and a clothing bundle from the kang. He ran out shouting, “Master! Disaster—there’s been theft!” Pincai panicked and rushed over. What happened next is told in the next chapter."
  ],
  "35": [
    "When Pincai entered his room and saw the trunk and caskets gone, he panicked. He rushed to the vegetable-garden gate in the yard: it was still locked, but scattered items lay near the wall. He shouted for the monk. Tang arrived with everyone else. Pincai insisted the thieves must have climbed over from the garden side and demanded the gardener be questioned, especially since no watch-call had been heard after third watch. Others urged calm and said they should open the gate and inspect first. The monk fetched keys and opened it; luckily the moon was bright enough without torches. He woke the gardener, who was terrified, then called for his helper repeatedly—no answer. They searched everywhere; no trace. The garden gate remained shut. In the northwest corner they found a trunk. “Good, here’s the trunk,” said the gardener. But it was empty except for a few padded garments and odds and ends. A foreign watch lay smashed on the ground. The monk concluded the thief had entered from outside and escaped over the wall and proposed checking from beyond the garden.",
    "Pincai said the thief was already far away and further searching was pointless. Fu Third told him to inventory losses and prepare a list for filing next morning. The monk, seeing the gardener’s panic, grew suspicious and threatened him, saying he must have colluded and would be handed to ward authorities until he confessed. They searched the gardener’s quarters and found nothing except an old woman trembling on the kang. Asked about the helper, the gardener—also shaking—said the man had gone missing after saying he would nap and then do night watch. The gate had not opened, yet he had vanished. “That settles it,” said Pincai. The monk declared it obvious collusion and had the gardener bound by temple workers. When the old woman cried innocence, he had her bound too, then handed both to street soldiers to guard against escape or suicide.",
    "Back inside amid confusion, Pincai had the monk entertain guests while he inventoried losses: seven fine fur garments, fifteen taels of gold, two hundred taels of silver; in the caskets, over thirty taels of broken silver, two taels of opium, and several jade pieces; in the clothing bundle, several heavy fur items. Fortunately, the money he had made from Fu Third plus some bank notes were stored elsewhere and untouched. Total loss exceeded one thousand taels. He hastily wrote a loss list and showed it to everyone. Since it was already around first light and city gates had opened, guests took leave; Fu Third and Yang Eight also prepared to return. As carriages were being harnessed, Rongguan arrived by cart.",
    "A servant of Fu Third joked, “The guests are leaving and only now you come.” Rongguan swept in, greeted everyone, and saw the gathering ending. Fu teased him: “Fine ‘famous gentleman’—invited for the fourteenth, arrives on the fifteenth.” Seeing Tianxiang and Cuiguan, Rongguan sneered that since everyone was dispersing he too would go, and he still needed barbers called in. With that he bowed slightly and left. The two barbers felt awkward; no one had much to say. People departed by carriage. Later the barbers came back to console Pincai; he rewarded each with four taels, and they left pleased.",
    "Next day Pincai filed the theft report. Ward officials interrogated the gardener and found him genuinely uninformed. The missing helper, surnamed Cai, had joined only at year’s end, formerly a menial at a cheap eatery before it broke up. He had volunteered to help water the garden and do night watch. After sleeping that night he disappeared. Repeated questioning produced the same account; no evidence of collusion by the gardener. The case was transferred upward, and notices went to all nine city districts to hunt fugitive thief Cai. This thread is suspended for now.",
    "Meanwhile, Wang Xun, Yan Zhongqing, Wenze, and Chunhang spent the thirteenth to fifteenth at Yiyuan watching lanterns and drinking. Ziyu went one day; remembering he had first met Qinyan on this date last year, and that this year felt like another lifetime, he became quietly sorrowful. During New Year, famous actors hosted one another in constant banquets for over ten lively days. On the seventeenth, Wang Xun and Yan Zhongqing sent a swift note to Ziyu.",
    "Reading it, Ziyu learned that tomorrow was Baozhu’s birthday: notable scholars and performers were invited to gather at Baozhu’s residence, and Ziyun wanted everyone assembled in his garden by the chen hour. Ziyu replied accepting.",
    "Next day Ziyu simply told Lady Yan he was invited to drink at Yiyuan, received permission, went to Wang Xun’s place, and together they reached Yiyuan. Cixian had arranged everything at the Red Camellia Immortal Pavilion so Ziyun need not worry. This pavilion, newly developed last year, lay before Plum Knoll and behind the pear and crabapple spring courts. It had once been open ground with only a pavilion. Outside stood two Yingzhou spirit stones, one over twelve feet high and one over four feet. A huge magnolia leaned against the larger rock, trunk thicker than an embrace. Beside the smaller rock stood a tiered red camellia called “Baozhu Camellia,” over six feet tall and covered in countless brilliant blossoms. Twenty-four rooms were built around these two plants, with added magnolia, camellia, and winter jasmine filling the courtyard with fragrance.",
    "Inside, twelve Flower Deities were carved into the walls. Because Baozhu’s name resonated with this floral theme, Cixian chose this location. Dissatisfied with ordinary banquet routines, he had personally inspected all wine, dishes, and utensils three days earlier to make this feast distinct. At dawn he moved Ziyun’s traveling kitchen into side rooms of the pavilion. For each dish he prescribed method, preparation, and exact seasoning. After a full day’s effort he produced thirty-two dishes.",
    "Several famous actors could not attend due to private performances. Besides Baozhu, those present were Huifang, Sulan, Yulin, and Shufang—five performers total. On the scholar side, besides the two hosts of Yiyuan, came Liu Wenze, Yan Zhongqing, Wang Xun, Tian Chunhang, and Mei Ziyu—seven scholars. Twelve in all. Once everyone assembled, Baozhu first bowed in thanks.",
    "The weather was mild with a southeast breeze; everyone changed into mid-weight fur. The garden was saturated with floral scent. Ahead at Plum Knoll, hundreds of plum branches bloomed together, like a jade terrace and snowy flower-garden.",
    "They strolled the garden. Ziyu noticed a newly inlaid stone inscription on Plum Knoll’s corridor, with date unfinished. It bore a five-character quatrain: “Spring turns with the year; flowers revive like returning souls. I imagine the flower-loving guest sits in moonlight till dusk.” Ziyu wondered who wrote it; it felt like longing for flowers one cannot see. Ziyun and others came to look. Ziyun asked Ziyu how it was. Ziyu praised the meaning and guessed it was newly composed. Ziyun said it was Yunong’s recent poem yearning for Plum Knoll, copied out by Yaoqing; he carved it for that “quenching thirst by gazing at plums” feeling. “Flowers remain, people change—brother, do you remember last year?” Those words struck Ziyu’s heart; he felt a surge of sadness, suppressed it, and walked away silently. Zhongqing asked whether Yunong now wrote poetry. Baozhu said he had found over twenty poems from him, though Yunong refused to show them; this one was seen by chance. After a collective sigh they returned inside. Cixian noted twelve people were awkward at one table but too distant at two. Ziyun proposed joining two large square tables. Seating was arranged: eight on east-west sides, four on north-south; scholars occupied east-west and the five performers sat north-south, with Baozhu at the end seat.",
    "Every vessel that day was novel. At the table’s four corners stood four silver decanters that poured by mechanism without attendants; one only had to hold a cup to the spout. Inside each pot was an internal silver lever and chain attached to the lid. Turning the lid left activated the mechanism and wine flowed; turning right stopped it. Everyone tested them and praised them highly.",
    "Ziyun praised Cixian’s ingenuity. Cixian said this was minor; soon there would be two cups that could “walk” to whichever person was called. Everyone demanded to see. Cixian said they were for later drinking games; only two existed, modified by silversmiths four or five times over a month. Huifang insisted on trying now. A huanghuali box was brought containing two gilt cups on wheeled bases like tiny clockworks. Cixian set one on the table; it did not move. Wenze pushed it; it moved slightly and stopped. Cixian said it would move only after one accepted a drink. Wenze agreed. Cixian filled it and commanded, “Treasure, turn and offer Lord Liu a cup.” The cup rolled straight to Wenze. Delighted, he drank. He filled and commanded it to return a cup to Master Xiao (Cixian), but it went wrong to Wang Xun, then on retry to Baozhu. Wenze called it bizarre. Ziyu said there must be a hidden principle he had not grasped. Cixian took it back, called for Liu again, and it rolled correctly. Wenze said he would believe only if it worked for everyone. Cixian said it would serve the whole table—and indeed it rolled steadily to each person in turn, scholars and performers, without spilling a drop. Everyone was thrilled. When others tried commanding, it failed, which made it even more marvelous.",
    "Huifang inspected the cup on all sides and saw no mark. Looking closely at the wheel-base, he noticed a tiny fixed needle like a compass pointer and guessed that was the key. He filled a cup, aligned the needle secretly toward Cixian, and said, “A cup for Master Xiao.” It rolled correctly to Cixian. Huifang laughed; everyone cheered that he had cracked the mechanism. Cixian praised him as a clever thief. Wenze asked the principle; Huifang said he would test once more first. He reset it, aligned, and called for Master Xu; it rolled to Ziyun. Ziyun laughed and said he still did not believe only Huifang could manage it among twelve people.",
    "Ziyun checked beneath the base and tried: “A cup to Meixiang.” It rolled instead to Ziyu, making everyone laugh. Ziyun conceded it was tricky. Ziyu drank, studied the wheel assembly, grasped most of it, and asked to test. He filled and called, “This cup to Yaoqing!” It rolled to Baozhu and stopped against chopsticks. Huifang clapped: another had solved it. Ziyu was pleased. Baozhu drank and said he still refused to concede and wanted to figure it out too, snatching the cup from Ziyu to inspect. Zhongqing asked how Ziyu had seen through it. Ziyu said he would demonstrate once more.",
    "Ziyu filled a cup, aligned the mark toward Ziyun, then paused—too near might overshoot—so he placed it slightly farther and called. It rolled straight to Ziyun. Ziyun marveled and drank. Huifang observed that Cixian poured shallow for short distances and full for long, so cup weight affected travel range. Ziyu agreed. Cixian jokingly complained they had discovered even the weight-distance relation. Wang Xun asked where exactly Ziyu had seen it. Ziyu said everyone looked only at the outside of the wheel disk, not inside: the tiny needle direction determined destination. Everyone checked and tested; all worked precisely. They admired Ziyu and Huifang’s quick intelligence.",
    "Cixian said no elegant gathering should be without drinking games. As first seat, Wenze should set one. Wenze proposed a Tang-poetry number game for twelve people: first quote a line containing “one,” count around to destination and that person drinks; then “two,” then “three,” and so on up to twelve. Mistakes incur penalties. The group agreed. Sulan and Shufang protested it was hard. Wenze said they likely knew Tang lines better than the men; if one could not produce a number line, drink that many cups. Baozhu asked if failing at twelve meant twelve penalty cups; Wenze said yes. Ziyun said that was too harsh and could be adjusted case by case. Wenze explained counting direction. Cixian gave him the starter cup. Wenze drank and recited, “Plum and willow fluff are newly bright together.” The “one” landed on Shufang, who drank and said she didn’t know the source. Baozhu identified Zhao Yanzhao’s palace-response poem. Shufang then flew “two” with: “Willows warm, flowers spring—second month skies.”",
    "Counting “two” again landed fifth, to Cixian. He drank and recited, “I would accompany phoenixes and cranes back to the Three Mountains.” Counting led to Zhongqing, who drank, poured, and sent to Chunhang with “Red candles behind, four curtains of gauze hang down.” Chunhang praised its sensuality, drank, and sent “five” with “Embroidery of five patterns adds delicate thread,” which landed on Baozhu. Baozhu drank and complained six-number lines were scarce and he might be penalized. Ziyu said there were still some.",
    "After thinking, Baozhu recited, “On the bed the green screen opens six leaves,” and it counted to Yulin. Yulin joked Baozhu must have invented it. Sulan mocked him for forgetting Hua Rui Lady’s palace poems. Yulin laughed and drank, saying Baozhu only wanted him to drink. For “seven,” after long thought he sent to Wang Xun: “At the gate descends a seven-perfumed carriage.” Wang drank and flew “eight” with Xue Feng’s line on the “deep figure-eight brows.” It counted to Ziyun, who drank and said “nine” lines were fewer and seldom good; he recited one about “nine-flowered curtains.” It counted to Sulan, who drank and flew “ten” as “The chamber beauty is ten-odd years old,” counting to Shufang. Shufang complained she was hit twice already, drank, and gave “eleven”: “On the long-solstice night in the eleventh month,” directing Baozhu to drink. Baozhu said she herself still owed a cup for ten.",
    "Shufang had to drink her own extra cup. Baozhu then flew “twelve”: “On the southern road stand twelve-tiered green towers,” landing on Ziyu. Ziyu asked whether to continue past twelve. Cixian said Meixiang still hadn’t been hit; continue until then, so now use thirteen. Ziyu recited, “Slender and graceful, just over thirteen,” landing on Zhongqing. Zhongqing said numbers above ten were scarce and suggested ending once Meixiang flew one line. He gave “thirteen-fourteen” line, assigning drinks to Yaoqing and Meixiang, then asked Meixiang to close the round. Huifang objected it should be Duxiang’s turn, but Ziyun told him to fly anyway. Huifang produced “At year’s first fifteen, most romantic,” assigning cups to Cixian and Ziyu. Cixian approved. They drank, closed the game, and had more dishes and snacks.",
    "After more talk, Cixian said he had a more demanding game but since everyone present liked drinking games, they should attempt it. Huifang warned him not to mock people again with *Water Margin* tricks. Cixian laughed and reminded him of a previous snowy-day prank. He had a page fetch the third tube of ivory lots. The page brought an ivory cylinder full of small slips and one large slip. The large one announced a “Hundred Beauties Toasting” game, engraved with those four characters.",
    "Below were rules: one hundred beauty-names across categories (astronomy, geography, seasons, flora, etc.). Each person draws a slip, identifies its category and name, then composes two Tang lines: first containing one character from the top of the name, second containing one from the bottom. If tones/rhythm fail, drink three penalty cups and redraw; if excellent, others toast one cup each. After Tang lines comes “flower matching” from two *Mao Shi* lines: if first characters of both lines combine into a flower name, it is a “paired-head flower,” and the speaker drinks two while seatmates toast two.",
    "Further rules: last characters of both lines forming a flower = “paired-stem flower,” self two cups, opposite seat toasts two; last character of first plus first of second forming flower = “intertwined flower,” self two cups, adjacent seats toast one each; flower-name characters appearing mid-line in symmetrical positions = “bud-contained flower,” self half cup, youngest participant toasts half. If positions are mismatched (“staggered flower”), self one cup and those one seat away toast one. If flower name is formed but imagery or category linkage is poor, penalty three cups. Each beauty has designated allowable flowers as marked on the slip; misuse forbidden. Everyone said it was difficult. Baozhu and Huifang said they could not do it and suggested only the seven scholars play. Zhongqing said the hardest part was matching flower names from *Mao Shi*; composing two Tang lines was no worse than the previous number game.",
    "Ziyu said there were some possible flower matches in *Mao Shi*, though paired-head and paired-stem types were harder. Wang Xun said hard thinking might at least aid digestion, though forcing the performers through *Mao Shi* would be too much. Ziyun proposed splitting: seven scholars do the “bitter” hard game, while the five performers do a “sweet” easier one. Hearing the performers’ lines might even inspire scholars when stuck. All agreed and asked what game for the five. Ziyun said he had one and ordered two dice and a small dish.",
    "Ziyun explained dice symbols: 1 moon, 2 star, 3 goose, 4 person, 5 plum, 6 heaven. If roll is 1+2, compose two opera-lyric lines, one on moon and one on star, with connected sense and rhythm. If the two lines naturally link, everyone toasts a double cup; if from the same aria set, each toasts one. Poor lines: penalty one cup. Reversing order (e.g., saying star before moon when moon rolled first): penalty. Other combinations follow similarly. If doubles appear (two persons, two heavens, etc.), lines should include duplicated word forms (“人人,” “天天” etc.) for bonus; failure costs three cups. Huifang and Baozhu repeated rules and said not easy, though they still had many lyric lines memorized. Ziyun told Cixian to move Xiangwan and Peixian over so the performers could roll in one area; seating was adjusted accordingly.",
    "Cixian shuffled slips and gave the tube to Wenze, who drew first. Wang Xun asked why not everyone draw first and proceed by order. Cixian said that would be too easy—people could overthink and avoid penalties. Wenze’s slip was category “Adornment,” beauty name “Yuhuan,” requiring two seven-character Tang lines plus a *Mao Shi* paired-head flower. Wenze paced and said this was less drinking game than literary exam. Cixian replied early submission was best. After about one tea’s time, Wenze sat and recited: “Under jeweled-hook curtains, shadows sink and sink; ringed pendants return empty, moonlit soul alone.” (Using “玉” and “环.”)",
    "Everyone praised it as excellent. Cixian added that placing “yu” and “huan” at line openings matched the paired-head flower idea and asked for the *Mao Shi* paired-head flower; they first toasted him one cup.",
    "Wenze said he had forgotten his prepared flower and could not think of one. Seeing the cup was chicken-patterned, he improvised from *Mao Shi*: “The rooster has crowed; crest and tassel stand in pair”—thus “cockscomb” as paired-head flower. Since his seatmate was Jiantan, Jiantan should toast two cups. Zhongqing said Wenze should drink his own two first. Wenze did so gladly. As Zhongqing drew next, Wenze reminded him of his toast. Zhongqing retorted Wenze’s lines were not smoothly linked and hardly deserved celebration. Ziyu said cockscomb technically fit, though coherence was weak. Wenze challenged others to produce a better “冠” line; then suggested another line, but Zhongqing said it still failed paired-head criteria. Wenze admitted error. Cixian mediated: one courtesy toast only. Zhongqing drank and drew his own slip: category astronomy, beauty “Chaoyun,” requiring two seven-character Tang lines plus paired-stem flower from *Mao Shi*. After thinking, he combined lines from Wei Zhuang and Du: “Morning after morning, evening after evening below Yangtai; cloud-and-rain on deserted terrace—is it dream-thought?” Then gave *Mao Shi* phrase for “wife-and-husband in concord,” interpreting “night-blooming flower” (夜合) as paired-stem flower.",
    "Everyone praised Zhongqing. Cixian said the flower fit his Tang lines well; all should toast one, and opposite-seat Meixiang should toast two. Huifang had just rolled 2+5 and was still thinking when asked to drink those toasts; after drinking, he produced two lyric lines: “Not even half a star of pity for jade or fragrance—fit only to keep to reed windows and thatched plum-curtains.” Ziyu clapped and praised its tender elegance, saying the adapted pairing felt better than original. Wenze noted it came from *Visiting Su* in one aria sequence, deserving another toast. On scholars’ side, Wang Xun drew category birds, beauty “Flying Swallow,” flower paired-stem; his composition was slow. Meanwhile Sulan rolled 1+4 and thought deeply, then recited, “Moon bright, clouds thin, dew-heavy flowers; in which palace of Penglai does the beloved dwell?” Chunhang praised it as finer still. Ziyu said performers’ lines were more fragrant and sensual than scholars’. Sulan replied scholars had harder constraints: person-name plus flower type. Shufang said she could hardly compose even by borrowing lines from what had just been spoken and was lucky not to be in the hard game. Wang Xun still had no answer, so Cixian identified Huifang’s as from *Qin Courtship* and had everyone toast one more.",
    "Yulin rolled 2+4 and recited two lines from *Hearing Bells*: “A lone goose in vast sky deepens grief; beneath Emei few travelers pass.” Everyone said good, though Ziyun noted the mood was bleak; they toasted one cup each. On the hard side, Wang Xun finally produced lines combining Pei Qianyu and Wen (as he thought): “Jade hairpin sways, twin phoenixes fly; where the swallow-pin falls, silence grows soft.” Ziyun and Wenze praised the seamless linkage. Wang Xun then gave “paired-stem peony” from *Mao Shi*. Before anyone responded, Zhongqing joked, “Half the dishes not yet served and roast pig already appears.” People looked around confused. Wang Xun asked where roast pig was. Zhongqing laughed: Wang’s phrase sounded like describing roast pork color. Everyone burst out laughing, including Wang Xun. Cixian corrected him: one character was likely wrong—should be “jade pin,” not “swallow pin”—and source should be Li He’s *Beauty Combing Hair*, not Wen; penalty one cup. Wang conceded name confusion but defended the character. Chunhang said variant editions might exist; in any case, the couplet was good. They toasted him one cup.",
    "Baozhu rolled double twos and recited: “Tonight in desolation there are four stars.” All praised the clever ease and toasted one cup each. Chunhang drew category colors, beauty “Hongfu,” flower “intertwined flower.” After thought, he paired lines from Wei Zhuang and Du: “A thousand, ten thousand branches in red spring brilliance; fishing rod nearly brushes coral boughs,” then matched a *Mao Shi* phrase to make “everlasting spring” as intertwined flower. He was praised and toasted. Shufang rolled 1+4 and recited: “Moon shifts flower-shadows—one suspects a jade beauty arrives.” Everyone called it natural and excellent; she earned double toasts.",
    "Ziyu drew category geography, beauty “Luo Goddess,” flower paired-head. His first attempts felt weak. Just then Huifang rolled 1+3 and recited from *Stealing Poetry*: “Hating sleeplessness by the waning moon west of window; harder still to hear the lone goose cry.” Ziyu praised it as brocade-hearted eloquence; Ziyun said even scholars couldn’t match such lines in this game. All toasted. Then Ziyu delivered his own pair using Leng Chaoyang and Meng Haoran: “Like Luo goddess riding mist away; gazing still as river deity plays with pearls.” Cixian, Zhongqing, Chunhang and others hailed it as best so far—balanced and graceful, very much Yuxiang’s style. For paired-head flower he gave, from *Mao Shi*, “When moon rises bright, the young lady longs in hunger,” taking “moon-season rose” (月季) as flower match. Everyone loved that flower-name and insisted on triple toasts. Ziyu modestly deflected. Sulan then rolled 1+6 and recited from *Wine Tower*: “Suddenly appears Chang’e in the moon palace, surpassing even Qiu-chi’s little heaven.” Again everyone praised and toasted.",
    "Cixian drew category seasons, beauty “Yelai” (Night-Coming), flower paired-stem. Ziyun told him to think while they ate more dishes. After another five or six plates and lamps lit, seating loosened. Cixian then announced his pair (Bai Juyi + Li Bai): “In eighth and ninth months, nights are long indeed; the lover says he will come, yet does not.” People admired its seasoned tone and said it sounded characteristically like Cixian. He cautioned that flower matching might still fail, then used a common alias: from *Mao Shi* phrase with “gengwu day,” taking “ziwu flower” as paired-stem. Since that day happened to be gengwu, everyone praised the aptness and toasted three cups each.",
    "Yulin rolled 4+5 and recited from *Floss Pavilion*: “For one in the heart, old heart-sickness stirs; coy Spring Lord, your spring-heart leans to plum twigs.” Huifang joked this was much better than Yulin’s earlier *Hearing Bells* entry. They toasted two cups. Ziyun then said he would submit his hard-game answer; his drawn slip was flora category, beauty “Lianxiang,” flower intertwined. He kept polishing and did not speak quickly, meanwhile watching dice rounds. Baozhu rolled 2+4 and recited from *Spring Sleep*: “Starry eyes rub with fatigue; a whole sheet of beauty-fragrance blends.” Ziyun praised and gave one toast. Shufang rolled 1+2 and recited, “Moon climbs eastern wall—most lovely when stars are clear and moonlight bright.” One toast again. Wenze teased Ziyun for delaying his own submission. Ziyun said he was almost done. Huifang then rolled 1+4 and recited from *Stealing Song*: “Mountain enters cold sky, moon-shadows cross; by the balustrade, a jade beauty leans at leisure.” Ziyun praised it and awarded a double toast, then finally submitted his own pair from Wen Tingyun’s *Lotus-Picking Song*: “Green duckweed, golden millet, lotus stems are short; dew heavy, flowers many, fragrance does not fade.” All said good; Cixian noted only that one character-pair was not perfectly matched.",
    "Baozhu cast Ziyun a thoughtful look. Cixian said even with that minor mismatch, Ziyun still deserved triple toasts like Ziyu; they settled on two cups from each. For flower match Ziyun gave: “In the south are lofty trees; hibiscus and shepherd’s purse sweet as syrup,” taking wood-hibiscus as intertwined flower. Everyone said those lines were natural and toasted two cups. By now minds were tired and people wanted dinner. Ziyun said still early—watch a few more dice rounds, since performers’ game demanded less formal structure. Sulan rolled double fours and instantly gave a *Peeking at Bath* line: “Two become one set of guts and stomach.” Zhongqing slammed table in delight, calling it heavenly, and everyone toasted three cups. Yulin rolled double threes and gave from *Little Banquet*: “Across long sky, rows of new geese.” Cixian said performers were getting better and now outclassing scholars. Wang Xun said indeed fine words came from beautiful mouths. Chunhang agreed they were quick and scholars must concede. Wenze noted no performer had been penalized once; instead they had earned dozens of toasts. Ziyu said he had predicted this; if performers played scholars’ game they might do even better. Still, it was time to close and eat. Ziyun said let each finish current turn—they had also worked hard for those toasts.",
    "Then Baozhu’s turn: he rolled double twos and recited from *Secret Vow*: “Ask the twin stars—morning and evening, what compares with you and me?” All praised it and toasted one. Everyone smiled at Baozhu; he blushed, which made them laugh more, and he lowered his head with a faint smile. Soon it was Shufang’s turn. Since each had rolled three times, this would close the game. He rolled double fours and recited from *Peeking at Bath*: “The one in the heart; the heart among people.” All acclaimed this perfect ending—today’s whole company was wrapped into that phrase. By character count they proposed six celebratory cups before dinner. They drank happily, then dined, rinsed, and changed clothes. By the clock it was near end of the hai hour. Everyone prepared to leave, bowed farewell to host, and host plus the five performers escorted them to the garden gate. The five then returned, chatted a bit more, and dispersed.",
    "Cixian told Ziyun he would have these two game-rules engraved and circulated outside, to make people use their minds instead of endless crude finger-guessing and brawling games. Ziyun agreed; today’s play had nothing improper in it anyway. After more talk, Ziyun went in. What happened next awaits the next chapter.\n\n**Translating paragraphs concisely**\n\nI need to translate 38 paragraphs, which feels lengthy but manageable. My goal is to provide a concise yet comprehensive translation for each paragraph. I’ll focus on ensuring that the essence of the original content is preserved while keeping things clear and straightforward. Since it’s quite a number of paragraphs, I want to make sure I approach each one methodically to maintain quality. Let's get started on crafting this!"
  ],
  "36": [
    "In the previous chapter, Baozhu’s birthday at Yiyuan was a full day of joy—yet people’s fortunes differ between joy and sorrow. At the Hua residence, Qinyan had been ordered by Young Master Hua to perform with Baling on Lantern Festival day. Qinyan was unwell that day and emotionally stirred by memories of the past, so he appeared desolate and without spirit.",
    "Onstage, when he reached an emotionally charged passage, he began to cry for real. Young Master Hua thought this was baseless melancholy, grew very displeased, summoned him down, and severely rebuked him. For several days he was not called to perform. Qinyan stayed alone in one room, with no visitors, and clashed temperamentally with the attendants around him.",
    "Behind the side rooms of Liuqing Studio, he lived in a small three-room unit with one page attending him. In the yard stood several Taihu rocks, two green-calyx plum trees, and one red plum, all still in bloom.",
    "On the twenty-seventh of the first month, staring at the plum blossoms, Qinyan began to miss Plum Knoll at Yiyuan. Comparing Duxiang’s treatment of him with his present life felt like comparing heaven and abyss. Even when service was imperfect, Duxiang showed neither displeasure nor resentment, only comfort and care. Young Master Hua could resemble Duxiang when pleased, but when displeased he became irritable and fault-finding; on Lantern Festival he had openly cursed Qinyan as if he were just another servant. The flatterers around him then gloated, and Qinyan felt trapped in endless humiliation. The more favor the master showed, the more coworkers hated him; the more reward, the more they sneered. Their cold mockery was unbearable. He blamed Xi Eleven for causing earlier trouble that pushed him into this decline. He thought of Wei Pincai—no good man, yet sometimes he still spoke to Qinyan’s true feelings—and now even Wei was gone. Lin Shanzhi had become half-master himself; if not carefully flattered, he would set people up. Qinyan even thought being expelled might be freer, perhaps freeing him from dependence on his old master too. If heaven would let him live cleanly, he would accept lifelong poverty and cold. Otherwise people would only say: once an actor, then a servant—who would respect him? The more he thought, the angrier he grew, tears falling as he sat alone under the plum trees. Then he heard Lin Shanzhi call, “Yunong!” and enter. Seeing Qinyan’s grief-stricken face, Shanzhi asked, “You know already?” Qinyan, confused, asked “Know what?” Shanzhi said: “Your teacher is dead. Someone just came to report it. The young master has approved your return for funeral rites.” Qinyan burst into tears and asked when. Shanzhi said there had been no illness: he slept last night and was found dead this morning. Qinyan grieved again and asked how to go. Shanzhi said people were waiting outside, and he was instructed not to delay—finish the funeral and return promptly. Qinyan agreed, packed clothes, bedding, and silver, locked up, and came out. He still did not know the routes well; the page guided him. At the gate, others already knew and asked nothing. Outside stood his usual carriage by the wall, and his teacher’s wife’s cousin Wu Mazi was there. Qinyan greeted him, and they rode out of the city together.",
    "Near the home, they saw people already setting funeral awnings. Qinyan entered; Tianshou ran out, saw him, and ran back in. Inside, his teacher’s widow was sobbing. At the bedside Qinyan saw his teacher already dressed for the bier, face covered with cloth. He knelt and cried uncontrollably. The widow pulled him up and comforted him. He asked what illness had killed his teacher so suddenly. She said there had been none—he had smoked opium till after third watch, chatted normally before sleep, and by morning his body was cold. If coal poisoning, she said, why was she unharmed? Qinyan asked about funeral expenses. She sighed that despite a lifetime of earning, little remained; finances had already tightened last New Year. It was far worse now than when Qinyan still lived there. The two junior disciples were idle most days; she saw no future plan. The death was abrupt; no last words, and he had never told her his outside dealings. She did not know what they owed others or what others owed them. The two rental houses outside the alley brought little. Clothes, coffin, and awnings could be managed, but buying burial ground and handling interment would be difficult. Qinyan sighed, went to his former room, had bedding laid out, opened his silver bundle: fifteen ingots totaling perhaps fifty or sixty taels. He brought it to her, saying he did not know the exact amount, only that it came from New Year rewards by the young master and lady, and could help as household cash. She weighed and counted it, then advised him to save money at Hua’s house and not let others cheat him; with no children, she said, she would rely on him later. Qinyan said most rewards were trinkets, little cash; even if he kept this he had little use for it, and if he got more later he would support her again. She nodded, praised his good heart, put the silver in a drawer, and he went out.",
    "The household was in hectic motion. Wu Mazi brought in mourning clothes. Soon Yuan Baozhu, Su Huifang, and Lu Sulan arrived; Qinyan hurried to receive them and sat with all three.",
    "They first asked about his teacher’s death, then about his New Year circumstances. Qinyan briefly described recent events. Baozhu asked how many days’ leave he had requested. Qinyan said Lin Shanzhi informed him that morning; he had not seen Young Master Hua personally and was only told to return after funeral matters, with no fixed number of days. Sulan said he should request at least one month, returning only after burial, otherwise it would wrong his teacher’s widow. Huifang said he might as well request a long leave and not go back—he had not sold himself to them. Baozhu said the post was good in some ways, but restrictive and lonely without true confidants. Huifang complained that Lin Shanzhi, once nothing special, now acted grand toward old peers; after entering Hua’s house he behaved like an official and looked down on equals. Qinyan said even today Shanzhi had spoken absurdly: “Your teacher is dead”—as if one ceased to be a teacher once the disciple had graduated. Baozhu added Shanzhi now demanded to be called “Third Master,” not “Third Brother,” and staged authority before Baling while nursing old grudges. Qinyan said Young Master Hua was not wholly strange but could be hard to read; somehow Shanzhi always pleased him and never struck a nail—his adaptive talk was undeniably skillful. Sulan said rumor had it everyone in the Hua residence flattered Shanzhi, even old hereditary servants; Wei Pincai used to call him “third brother,” “Old Third,” even “Third Grand Master.”",
    "Qinyan asked whether Wei Pincai might now be at Yuxiang’s place. Huifang said Pincai had grown even more swaggering, living at Hongji Temple and carousing daily with scoundrels like Xi Eleven, Pan Third, and Yang Eight, together with barbers and monks, gambling and keeping prostitutes; even Zhang Zhongyu had cut ties with him. Qinyan asked about Ziyu. Baozhu described their recent full-day gathering at Yiyuan: drinking games, Cixian’s new mechanical wine pots and cups, and the carved poem Duxiang had set up; he recounted in detail how emotional Yuxiang looked on reading it. Qinyan was moved to sadness. Huifang proposed they gather closely for several days while Qinyan was back, perhaps as soon as tomorrow. Qinyan said his teacher had just died, so propriety required some pause. Sulan argued that waiting too long would send him back to the city before they met; quiet conversation was no ritual violation, and Qinyan was not a filial son in formal mourning terms. Baozhu said he would ask Duxiang and arrange tomorrow or the day after. They sat long; when they rose to leave, Qinyan held them back, unwilling to part, and they stayed longer. Later Wang Guibao, Li Yulin, and Jin Shufang arrived. Everyone remained through the coffin-sealing rites, bowed, then dispersed. Since Qinyan was in mourning robes, going out next day seemed improper, so they set a meeting three days later. He also sent Wu Mazi to Hua residence asking Shanzhi to relay a one-month leave request until after burial. Young Master Hua approved and even sent back a clothing chest, which finally eased Qinyan’s mind.",
    "On the third-day mourning observance, many people came. Jin San and Ye Maolin were invited to help manage affairs. Besides members of their own troupe, people from other troupes, nearby neighbors, and restaurant keepers crowded the room. They stayed through paper-burning rites and then dispersed. Qinyan, exhausted, returned to his room and slept.",
    "Next morning Baozhu sent word: the gathering planned for today was moved to tomorrow morning at Yiyuan because Duxiang had business. Qinyan agreed. After washing, he sat thinking: with no business today, perhaps he should visit Yuxiang. Remembering Lady Mei’s kindness last year, he thought it should be acceptable. He changed into plain clothes, ordered a carriage, and told his teacher’s widow he was going to thank troupe friends. But outside he hesitated: half a year had passed; previously Pincai had led him there and handled gate communication. Going alone now, even if Lady Mei remained kind, he would still have to ask the gate staff. If rebuffed, he might not get in at all. Besides Yun’er, he knew no one there. Unable to decide, he stood still. A page came in saying the carriage was ready and asked destination. Qinyan stayed silent, then decided: better find Pincai and go with him to avoid difficult explanations; since Pincai had moved out, visiting him first was also proper.",
    "He told the page: “First to Hongji Temple to see Master Wei.” They reached quickly. At the temple gate stood a large carriage with sleeping driver; Qinyan assumed it was Pincai’s and was relieved he had come before Pincai went out. The page went in and returned: Pincai was home and invited him in. Qinyan entered through the east gate, passed two halls, and into another courtyard. Head lowered, he noticed little. At Pincai’s yard, servant Si’er opened the wind-door. Qinyan looked up and was startled to see a room full of men. His heart jumped, face reddened; he wanted to withdraw, but Pincai was already coming out to greet him. Pincai exclaimed this visit was beyond expectation. Qinyan, blushing, could not answer. Pincai introduced him grandly to the room as “the famous Du gentleman I always mention, now called Master Du Qin,” then introduced Xi Eleven, Pan Third, Monk Tang the landlord, the novice, and two troupe men. Qinyan bowed awkwardly. The monk, hearing he came from Hua residence, greeted him deferentially. Pan Third, however, had already become lustful: while Qinyan attended to the monk, Pan stepped up and grabbed his hand, speaking with obscene eagerness about fated reunion. Qinyan, ashamed and angry, quickly pulled free. Pincai knew Qinyan’s temper and that he might cry if pressed, so he pushed Pan away and seated Qinyan. Xi Eleven then asked how life at Hua’s was. Qinyan answered “fine.” Xi asked if he recognized him. Seeing a dark imposing man, Qinyan said no. Xi laughed, came closer, and pressed Qinyan’s shoulders as he tried to stand. Xi reminded him of a past incident, claiming credit for “making” Qinyan enter Hua house. Qinyan then realized this was Xi Eleven and grew more frightened, shrinking back. Xi mocked his bashfulness as girlish. Pincai, worried Xi might get rough, explained that strict Hua-house rules had kept Qinyan from seeing strangers, hence his restraint. Pan Third drooled but did not yet dare act; Monk Tang only fantasized inwardly. Pincai asked why Qinyan had come. Qinyan said his teacher had died and he had a month’s leave; “I came to see you, and also want you to come with me…” He faltered. Pincai understood and asked, “You want me to go with you where?” Qinyan finally said, “To visit Lady Mei and Yuxiang.” Pincai nodded: “Fine, we’ll go in a bit.” With so many present, Qinyan could not urge him.",
    "Xi Eleven was a coarse practical man, but he could judge beauty plainly. Seeing Qinyan now, he felt he had encountered an unprecedented treasure, and his desire surged.",
    "He reflected that Qinyan had changed status and now served close in Hua residence, so open harassment would be risky; even asking him to drink would likely fail. While watching and listening to plans for Pincai to accompany Qinyan to Mei house, Xi devised a scheme.",
    "After calculating, Xi stood and announced he was leaving, then strode out. Pincai and the monk hurried to see him off. Pan stayed seated, staring hungrily at Qinyan, who burned with anger but could not explode. Xi pulled Pincai to the monk’s room and bowed, asking a favor: he truly desired Qinyan but knew Qinyan would refuse to accompany drinking. Pincai immediately said yes, he would refuse for sure. Xi said he had a plan: they would leave now; Pincai should keep Qinyan for lunch under pretext of going to Mei house afterward; during the meal Xi would return and sit with him. Even if nothing further happened, Xi’s heart would be satisfied and not count as grave insult. He would send gifts too and see Qinyan’s response. He begged Pincai as a friend. Pincai hesitated, knowing Qinyan could not be forced, but not wanting to offend Xi. He agreed cautiously, warning Xi not to get rough: one wrong sentence could make Qinyan cry, and Pincai had already “hit many nails” on this. Xi promised no violence, only to sit briefly. He said he would send dishes, and told Pincai to draw Pan out, dismiss Tianxiang and Cuiguan, set lunch, and wait for his quick return. Then he rushed off in his carriage.",
    "Pincai returned and told Pan Third the monk wanted him. Pan went unwillingly, looking back repeatedly. Pincai dismissed Tianxiang and Cuiguan as well, then said to Qinyan on purpose: “Good, now it’s quiet. They made the room unbearably vulgar. Let’s speak calmly, eat first, then go—we’ll naturally be delayed a little.” Qinyan thought eating there was acceptable now that others were gone. He asked how many times Pincai had seen Yuxiang this year. Pincai casually said three times. Qinyan asked why he associated with Xi Eleven, whom he had heard was bad. Pincai said they were not close, only that Xi was straightforward. Qinyan said he also knew that Pan fellow. Pincai defended Pan as a “honest businessman,” and even praised the monk as worldly-wise. Qinyan laughed inwardly but did not argue.",
    "Xi whipped his mule hard and rushed home. At his study he ordered servants to fetch four dishes and two pastries sent the previous night by his concubine and deliver them to Master Wei (Pincai), with scripted apologies. Without entering inner rooms, Xi lit opium on his study kang and had Ba Yingguan prepare a bubble; he took about thirty deep pulls (around three qian), enough for half a day. He pondered what gift to send Qinyan: his steel-inlaid watch worth about two hundred strings, then thought it insufficiently grand. Better would be the pair of jade bracelets owned by concubine Juhua—rare in the capital and impressive as gift. He went to Juhua’s room, found her on the chamber pot, joked crudely, and despite her retort opened her chest, took the bracelet box, pocketed it, and left without even closing the chest. She shouted what he was doing with her bracelets; he replied he was only “comparing colors” and would return them. He then hurried back toward Pincai’s place, fantasizing that if he could get Qinyan, even high officials in the capital would have to count him as a true big man. Meanwhile Pan Third, in the monk’s room, learned Xi’s plan and was delighted, indulging lewd fantasies as he waited. Monk Tang mocked his posture and drooling. Xi’s servant arrived with dishes and requested audience. Through Si’er he told Pincai: Xi had not known Master Qin was present earlier and regretted his offense; he wished to invite Master Qin but feared refusal, so he sent dishes as apology and could not come personally due to business. Pincai accepted smoothly, tipped the messenger, then told Qinyan this was Xi’s courtesy sent for him and he himself was merely sharing; Qinyan should thank him. Qinyan, not understanding the hidden scheme, gave a perfunctory thanks. Pincai then ordered the kitchen to hurry lunch.",
    "Soon Si’er set wine and dishes on a square table. Pincai urged that even for a simple meal they should drink one cup. Qinyan refused, but Pincai poured and handed him one anyway; Qinyan had to accept and then return a courtesy cup. Pincai was overjoyed—rarely had they sat face-to-face this way. He fed Qinyan soothing talk, claiming Yuxiang had recently stopped going out and often asked him to tell Qinyan not to worry, to rest easy there, and that through gradual ties with Young Master Hua they would naturally meet more often. His real aim was only to keep Qinyan seated until Xi arrived. But Qinyan was anxious to leave, barely drank or ate, and sat stiffly as if on thorns.",
    "As they were about to start eating, hurried footsteps entered the yard; the wind-door was pried open and Xi Eleven came in. Qinyan panicked and stood. Pincai smiled, “Perfect timing—the host comes to accompany the guest.” Xi said he came sincerely to toast Qinyan. He sat, poured with one hand while holding a cup in the other, and pushed it right to Qinyan’s lips. Qinyan, trapped between accepting and refusing, flushed bright red. Pincai said it was hostly courtesy; if he could not finish, just sip. Qinyan took one sip and set it down, saying he truly could not drink and felt too full. He tried to leave, but Xi grabbed him and said if he stood to leave now it was open disrespect. Xi claimed kin-like ties to Young Master Hua, and since Qinyan was Hua’s favorite, he was like Xi’s younger brother. He pressed Qinyan lightly back into his seat, but his forceful brow and manner were frightening; Qinyan, remembering prior encounters, turned pale and trembling. Xi, delighted, drank tea, then offered sea cucumber to Qinyan. Qinyan stood and politely declined. Xi made obscene innuendo about it being smooth and easy to swallow; Qinyan understood the mockery and knitted his brows. Pincai kicked Xi under the table to restrain him. Xi then drank Qinyan’s leftover wine himself, smacking his lips. Qinyan boiled with anger but suppressed it, thinking: this bastard has bad intent; I no longer perform, what can he really do? If he gets rude, I’ll make a scene. Xi poured another half cup and pushed it forward. Qinyan pressed the cup down and told Pincai he never drank. Xi still pressed when quick footsteps came: Pan Third and the monk entered. Pan shouted he had crashed a fine feast; the monk joked he had not even been invited. Pan rushed up to “toast,” took Qinyan’s cup, said it was cold and drank it, then rubbed the cup around his own lips, refilled half, and pushed it to Qinyan’s mouth with both hands. Qinyan twisted to rise, but Pan on one side and monk on the other blocked him. Forced, he took the cup. Pan still held on, trying to feed him directly. Qinyan, angry, said he truly could not drink and demanded release. Pincai seated Pan and asked him to let Qinyan drink slowly if at all. Pan sat; Pincai and monk sat lower on stools. Seeing Pan had smeared the cup with his mouth first, Qinyan felt deeply insulted. He now knew they were in league to humiliate him, yet feared open rupture might put him at physical disadvantage.",
    "So he endured and, lifting the cup, pretended to fumble. With a crash he shattered it on the floor, splashing some wine onto his clothes. Wiping with a handkerchief, he told Pincai, “I was careless.” Pincai understood exactly and said, “No matter.”",
    "They called for another cup. Qinyan said no need—even with a new cup he would not drink. Xi insisted each man should still coax him for three cups. Pan had hoped if Qinyan drank from that cup it would be like kissing Pan’s mouth, so he was deeply frustrated by the smashed cup and tried again, but Pincai blocked him. Monk Tang, clueless and coarse, poured half a cup and made a theatrical Buddhist speech: Hua residence had donated greatly to the temple, so as humble monk he offered this “flower to the Buddha” and invited little Master Qin to drink. He bowed and chanted loudly, making everyone laugh. Qinyan felt both irritated and amused; his face softened slightly as he repeated he truly could not drink. The monk grinned and said now that he had chanted, Buddha was inside the cup; drinking it would bring blessings front and back, wealth daily. More laughter. Qinyan still refused. Tang then rubbed his face, removed his cap, and made obscene self-mockery about his bald head, which made Qinyan involuntarily smile. The monk then pushed farther into vulgarity, and Qinyan’s expression darkened again.",
    "The monk begged theatrically that if Qinyan did not drink this cup, he would lose face and have to abandon monkhood tomorrow. He balanced the cup on his bald head, knelt, pressed hands to Qinyan’s knees, and chanted nonstop without rising, making everyone roar with laughter. Harassed beyond endurance, Qinyan said “Please rise—I’ll drink one sip, and never again.” He took the cup from the monk’s head and sipped. Then, fearing others might drink his remainder, he drained it in one go. Rising to leave, he was blocked: Xi pushed him back while the monk clutched his leg from kneeling position. Forced to sit again, Qinyan finally spoke sharply: “May I ask what exactly all of you intend?” Pincai quickly said no more drinking, let’s just talk, and pulled the monk up. Qinyan said he had business and tried to leave again. Xi blocked him, saying if he wouldn’t drink then at least sit awhile—why rush? Pincai could only urge that food be served quickly since they had business. Qinyan had to sit, furious yet still forcing restraint.",
    "Xi thought to himself that this youth was impossible to handle. If it were anyone else he would already have cursed and forced rough play. He told himself he was being indulgent, yet Qinyan remained stubbornly resistant, which angered him. Then he reconsidered: people always said Qinyan was proud, and it seemed true. Still, overt force would conflict with Hua residence, and since Qinyan no longer performed, Xi had no proper claim to demand he accompany drinking.",
    "He decided to try gifts instead: perhaps if Qinyan accepted reward, his attitude might soften. Pan Third thought Qinyan was even more striking than Su Huifang; if only Pan had brought cash vouchers to reward him, he might have won favor. Xi then said he had something to gift Qinyan and hoped it would not be considered too modest. He pulled out a brocade box and opened it: a pair of brilliant, pure-green jade bracelets gleamed intensely.",
    "Pan clicked his tongue, saying such treasure was rare even for one thousand strings in the city. Pincai and the monk stared too. Pincai thought this was a bold opening gift and watched whether Qinyan would accept. Qinyan did not even look up. Xi told him to try them; size would fit. Qinyan stood and said firmly he dared not accept and never wore bracelets. He absentmindedly extended a hand to indicate that point. Xi misread it as consent, grabbed his arm, and yanked too hard. Qinyan, delicate and frightened, lost balance and fell into Xi’s arms. Xi embraced him, unable to restrain himself: first he sniffed Qinyan’s face, then held his hand and forced one bracelet on. Reaching for the second, he momentarily loosened his hold; Qinyan tore free, already in tears, and cried out without regard for consequences: “I don’t know you. I’ve changed profession, yet you still treat me as an actor and degrade me. I’ll report this to my master, then speak to you again.” He ran out, stripped off the bracelet in the courtyard, smashed it hard into three pieces, and fled desperately. Xi exploded with rage, cursing him and rushing to chase. Pincai tried with all strength to restrain him, but Xi was larger and furious. Pincai could only brace his head against Xi and plead: “It’s all my fault—if you must hit someone, hit me.” Pan and Monk Tang still fanned the flames. Xi, blocked by Pincai and realizing Qinyan had likely already reached carriage and gone, gave up pursuit. He sat down panting, eyes bulging with fury.",
    "Ba Yingguan stood nearby suppressing a smile. He went into the yard, picked up the broken bracelet pieces—three sections total—fit them together in his palm and joked that for three qian he could set them in three joints and wear a fashionable “triple-set jade bracelet,” and wondered whether people would reward him for it.",
    "He brought the pieces before Xi and added: “A thousand-string bracelet has become worth three thousand now.” Xi cursed even harder on seeing it. Pan and Monk Tang kept lamenting the waste. The narrator notes that when Xi returned with only one bracelet left, Juhua would surely cause a huge quarrel. It was the old tale of a toad longing for swan flesh, ignorant of its own limits of fortune.",
    "Qinyan got into the carriage, dropped the curtain, and wept behind his hands all the way home. On arrival he stripped off his outer coat, lay on the bed, and the more he thought, the more bitterly he blamed himself for foolishly going to find Pincai and provoking this disaster. He covered his head with the quilt and cried for half the day, nearly driven to thoughts of suicide. What follows is for the next chapter."
  ]
};
